>felt like I was dragging on
You should never think like this when writing. Whenever your brain pitches a narrative idea that you feel like going with, let it grow naturally to its full length, without any external constraints. Artificially constraining the story often leads to it feeling unnatural and awkward, since you're "pruning" it. (I.e. "pruning" something that seemed good to your brain by merit of not being pruned.) By writing it out fully, you're subconsciously fleshing out the story according to your mental narratological image, which will make it more consistent.
(This really isn't always the case, but good practice. If you must abridge something, do it afterwards by revising.)
Anyway, we rarely have time to write things out fully, but it's a thought.

>Hot blooded mecha combat arena pilot (human) beats famous lion pilot
I don't know if "hot blooded" would be that interesting a character trait to go with here (two passionate/"hot-blooded" type characters clashing is only interesting for a few paragraphs), but I'm sure you'll nail it, man.
